04304nam a22006015i 9780292796485DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212002txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927964857 a10.7560/7254472doi  a(DE-B1597)587487  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aQL677.4b.F235 2002eb 7aNAT0040002bisacsh04a333.95/8162211 aFaaborg, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSaving Migrant Birds :bDeveloping Strategies for the Future /cJohn Faaborg. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2002  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 What Are Neotropical Migrants and Why Are We Concerned? -- t2 The Breeding Bird Survey: So Simple Yet So Complex -- t3 Is There Other Evidence for Large-Scale Population Declines? -- t4 Fragmentation Studies: Real Evidence of Local Declines -- t5 What Happens on Habitat Fragments? -- t6 Rethinking Avian Demography: Understanding Landscapes, Sources, Sinks, and Dispersal -- t7 Modern Management Guidelines for Breeding Migrant Birds -- t8 Migrant Wintering Ecology: Characteristics and Constraints -- t9 Population Limitation in Winter: Theory and Evidence -- t10 Migration Ecology: A Limiting Factor? -- t11 Migrant Birds in the New Millennium: What Do We Know? -- t12 Partners in Flight: How It Works and How You Can Help -- tPostscript -- tAppendix: Lists of Migrants for Partners in Flight -- tBibliography -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the 1980s, numerous scientific surveys documented both declining bird populations, especially among Neotropical songbirds that winter in the tropics, and the loss of tropical rain forest habitat. Drawing the seemingly obvious conclusion, scientists and environmental activists linked songbird declines to loss of tropical habitats and alerted the world to an impending ecological catastrophe. Their warnings led to the establishment of the Neotropical Migratory Bird Conservation Program, also known as Partners in Flight, the self-proclaimed largest conservation effort in history. Looking back over more than a decade of efforts to save migrant birds, John Faaborg offers the first serious evaluation of the state of songbird populations today, the effectiveness of conservation programs such as Partners in Flight, and the reliability and completeness of scientific research on migrant birds. Taking neither an alarmist nor a complacent approach, he shows that many factors besides habitat loss affect bird populations and that Neotropical migrants as a group are not declining dramatically, though some species adapt to habitat alteration more successfully than others. Faaborg's state-of-the-art survey thus clarifies the kinds of information we will need and the conservation efforts we should undertake to ensure the long-term survival of Neotropical migrant birds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aBird populations. 0aBirdsxConservation. 0aBirdsxMigration. 7aNATURE / Birdwatching Guides.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292796485423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292796485/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK